post_text:
Rockwell would like to welcome our new counselor, Shelley Hayes!

Shelley Hayes is passionate about helping youth and currently is doing that by providing school counseling. She has also worked with youth in residential treatment centers, as a therapeutic foster parent, and as a teacher at a school for students with autism. Shelley has 6 children of her own, as well as many animals. Shelley attended Utah State University for her master's degree in education, and the University of Nebraska for her other degrees. Shelley loves genealogy, puzzles, reading, and elephants.

Here we are at graduation week. Seniors and graduating Juniors, remember graduation practice is Wednesday the 3rd (check email) and graduation shifts are Thursday the 4th at 3:00, 4:30, 6:00, and 7:30 pm in the back parking lot. No spectators beyond what fits legally in the allotted car.

Office hours this week are Monday the 1st through Wednesday the 3rd, 9:00 am until 3:00 pm and Thursday the 4th, 9:00 am until 12:30 pm. It will be closed on Friday.

Questions and concerns can be sent to info@rockwellhigh.net or leave a message at (801) 789-7625. Work that has been arranged to be submitted may be sent to that email up until 3:00 pm on Wednesday the 3rd.

“May the 4th” be with you, teachers (and support staff)! Even in this semi-quarantined time we’re living, we still want you to know you’re appreciated. Hope you found your Star Wars-themed bags at your front doors over the weekend. Silly or cheesy though it may seem, we really feel “Yoda best!”

Students and families, a genuine and relatively easy way to express your appreciation is to send an email this week to teachers who help you reach for the stars. Watch for some other things we can do this week to let our teachers know how we feel about them.

post_text: Our thoughts and prayers are with Tye (class of 2020) and Brody (class of 2023) Zoellner, their mom, and sister, as well as their extended family and friends at the loss of their father, husband, family member, and friend, Chris Zoellner. Words always seem to fail to convey adequately the sorrow felt, but we hope in the coming days, weeks, months, and years, as a school community to always rally around this family and others who are faced with tragic loss and seemingly insurmountable challenges.

post_text:
Welcome to 2020 and our 2nd semester, 3rd term! Real quick:
(1) Glad to have Misty De Farias back! Her schedule is Monday through Thursday and then she will work from home on Fridays for the remainder of the school year.

(2) Students, please get to classes, on time, and do the work. No teacher wants to purposefully flunk any student, so help them help you.

(3) Schedules can be changed so just get a form from Misty Dipo. We want to help you all be successful, so help us help you.

(4) Seniors and those Juniors hoping to graduate early, we will be talking to you to make sure everyone is on track. Beside 26 credits as required by the state and our board, there is the state's civics test, a portfolio of best work, a service hours narrative, and a 5-year plan for after graduation that all need to be checked off.

(5) Lastly, please start mentally preparing for state testing coming soon. You can do hard things and you just need to do them the best you can.

Happy 2020 and we look forward to a great rest of the school year.

Down to the wire, as they say. We have 2 A days and 2 B days left until the end of the term. Here is what is going on this week:
1. Candy Cane Grams on sale through Wednesday, $1 - will be delivered on Thursday.
2. Wednesday the 18th is the Show Choir and Strings Concert, 7:00 pm.
3. Boys Bball at RSL, Wednesday, JV 5:15 and Varsity 7:00. They play at Providence Hall in Herriman.
4. High School Choir Concert, Thursday the 19th, 7:00 pm.
5. Girls Bball at Pinnacle Canyon in Price, 6:00 pm.
6. Special Monday edition of Saturday School on Monday, December 23rd, 8:00 am - 12 noon, for all high school students to make up attendance, work on Incompletes, and work on credit recovery, in the library.

Merry Christmas, Happy Holidays, and may 2020 see our vision (get it?) and outcomes improve. Have an awesome break, Marshals!

As a bonus, a Night of Shakespeare is Monday at 6 pm. All sorts of great news on a Friday.

post_text:
From CIEE:

Hello Rockwell Families and Friends!

I'm reaching out to all of you in hopes that someone might be in a position to help one of your students out. I wok with CIEE an exchange program for high school students. We have a boy from Poland named Michal that attends Rockwell. We are in need of a new host family for him.

He is really into photography and video editing. He loves learning new languages, He speaks Polish of course 🙂, fluent English, a bit of French and basics of Russian.
He likes tennis and swimming.

If you would like more information on how you can help this young man with one of the most amazing years of his life please send me a message, call me, or email me.

Thanks for your help!
Misti Gist
719-369-0208
mgist@ciee.org

post_text:
Looking to the south and to the north. Looks like our track and field project is getting closer to the finish line.

Speaking of finish line, there are 2 1/2 weeks left of the 1st quarter - ends Friday, October 11th. Please help reinforce with your student(s) the need to get to class and stay there in order to get the most out of each one. Final 1st quarter grades will be available by the end of the day on Wednesday, October 16th.

The Shakespeare Competition team will present their offerings before heading down to SUU next week at their annual Night of Shakespeare, Monday, September 30th, 6 pm - they compete October 3rd - 5th.

Rounding out the extracurriculars and heading to the end of their respective seasons are Volleyball, Cross Country, and Baseball. Volleyball plays at home Thursday night, JV 5:45 and Varsity 7:00 vs. APA-West Valley while Cross Country runs on Saturday at Orem's Lakeside Park. Lastly, Marshal Baseball will play a doubleheader Friday (2 & 4 pm) at Ogden's Lindquist Field, home of the Ogden Raptors. Let's go Rockwell.

post_text:
Thanks Marshals for a great start to the new year this past week. Remember, Monday and Wednesday are always A days and Tuesday and Thursdays are always B days. Just Friday rotates with this coming Friday the 23rd being a B day.

Also remember to use the planners to help you be successful this year. Getting to class regularly and on time and staying there are key elements to passing classes and earning your credits. Be willing to set your phones aside or in your backpacks so you can focus on doing your best daily for the rest of the year.

#WeAreMarshals

Today is the day, it’ll work out okay. Farewell to each grad; some are happy, some sad.
(Earning a diploma is no fad; actually, it is quite rad.)
So, with apologies to Suess and a limit of seat;
Facebook Live is the next best thing, so sweet!

Graduation is TONIGHT at 6:00 pm at Thanksgiving Point, though I was serious about limited seating. Tune in to Facebook Live to see it all. Congrats to our graduates - I know they’ll go far!

post_text: A HUGE Thank You to Direct Communications!
shared_text:
Direct Communications Utah is at Rockwell Charter High School.
October 29, 2018 at 10:39 AM · Eagle Mountain, UT ·

Candice Spivey of Rockwell Charter High School says: "Thank you, Directcom, for the generous donation. I can assure you that the money will be well spent here at Rockwell Charter High School. The plan is to use the $500 towards our athletics programs. This donation will help cover costs of equipments that is most definitely needed in our aging gym, as well as a few minor repairs that are needed for overall safety in a gym, that both serves our students and the community. Thank you again for the donation, we greatly appreciate Direct Communications and the support they’ve given our school over the years."

Rockwell has had a great first quarter:
1. The Shakespeare competition team won 1st place Sweepstakes in Cedar City in September.
2. Volleyball team qualified for the State 2A Tournament on the 26th at UVU, 5:30 pm, posting most successful season record in school history.
3. Cross Country’s Dylan Beck going to State 2A Cross Country meet on the 18th after taking 6th at Region (out of about 45-50 runners).
4. Student Government leaders attended a leadership conference at UVU in early October.
5. Marshals Baseball went undefeated (16-0) in Region play for the second year in a row and outscored the competition in the postseason tournament, 42-15, to bring home another Region Title.
Proud of these students, coaches, and advisers. WE ARE MARSHALS.

Hope everyone is enjoying summer. Some quick reminders:
Girls who will be in 9th through 12th during the upcoming school year who are interested in Drill, workshop Tuesday the 5th, 1:00 to 3:00 pm in the gym and the tryout will happen Wednesday the 6th, 1:00 to 3:00 pm in the gym. Questions? Contact the coach, mbeck@rockwellhigh.net.

Baseball Open Gym will be held once more this week on Thursday the 7th, 1:00 to 2:30 pm in the gym. For the next 2 weeks, we will be at Nolen Park, Tuesdays and Thursdays, 1:30 to 3:00 pm - weather issues, we will be at the gym at the school.

Last, but not least, Summer School session A is on right now, Monday through Thursday, 9:30 am to 1:00 pm. If you have any F's from 9th through 12th grades, meet with Mr. Beck or email him, dbeck@rockwellhigh.net. Be able to start the new school year on August 13th without those credit holes. (By the way, Open House for the new year is on Thursday, August 9th, 8:00 am to 6:00 pm.)

post_text: While it may look like vocational classes gone bad, these shots are of committed educators sacrificing in the name of charity. Paper bills subtract from the team total, though it is all added to the overall donation at the end. The result from the 2017 Change Wars: 7 families hopefully had a better Christmas. Way to be awesome, Marshals!

post_text: Congratulations to Mrs. Wendy Frederickson as she has been chosen as this week's employee of the week. Mrs. Frederickson was nominated because of her service-oriented attitude and willingness to go the extra mile for the students. She is always very attentive to each one of her student's needs, and it's important to her to get to know each one of them so she can understand what challenges each one of them face. If you've ever walked by, sat in, or ready an email about one of Mrs. Frederickson's classes, you'll know that she plans some of the best lessons and they are usually very fun, interesting and educational. Each lesson is created with her students in mind. And best of all she's a funny gal who appreciates life to the fullest, which is greatly appreciated by her co-workers! If you see Mrs. Frederickson this week make sure you give her a high five and congratulate her on being this week's employee of the week.

Simple as possible and directed at high school students and their parents:
Mentoring is a required class here.
It goes from 11:10 - 11:50, Monday - Thursday.
Lunch is 11:55 - 12:20. 4th period starts at 12:25.
With a 2.5 GPA and at least 92% attendance, students get an extra 15 minutes of lunch meaning they are excused at 11:35.
Low GPA and poor attendance, no extra lunch.
No extra lunch on Friday.
Students, please comply.
Parents, please reinforce this.

Thank you for your cooperation.

Mr. Beck

post_text:
Allow me to simplify things from Friday's events:

The fight was off school grounds and was NOT gang or drug related as rumored. Participants are suspended. Neither had previous major infractions. This is the first fight at Rockwell in a couple of years. Period.

The issue with a student taking unknown substances should demand our sympathy about why a young person would do that. No one forced the use of it. It is still unknown exactly what it was and, frankly, none of our business. My hope is that we would all hope and pray she is getting the help she needs. This is also a first in a couple of years. Period.

With this post and the email that went out Friday, we'd like to move forward. Thank you.

post_text:
Marshals, please consider these numbers:
540K+ high school Bball players
3.4% play in college (18,360+/-)
1.2% get drafted into NBA (220+/-)

This is not about trashing dreams, but about understanding that in order for dreams to come true, of any kind, you've got to put in the time and effort and persistence to realize them. You should have them. You should go after them. But, you should also be real honest with yourself about your dreams and what is required to make them happen.

If you have a plan A about playing professional ball of any kind, you have to be willing to sacrifice things that may be against you reaching your goal. Plan to make a difference in your community, in the lives of others. Make sure your plan A is a life plan you can be proud of when you go after it.

Spring break is the perfect time to consider your dreams, to aim for your future life. See you on the 10th.
